-- AMP, BHP, Centro, Coca-Cola, Dexus, NAB, Woodside: Australia Stock Preview
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 2010-10-17T21:33:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-17/amp-bhp-centro-coca-cola-dexus-nab-woodside-australia-stock-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed on Oct. 15. All
prices are from that day’s close unless otherwise stated.  The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in December lost
0.3 percent to 4,686 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank of New
York Australia ADR Index  declined 0.5 percent. The  S&P/ASX 200
Index  slipped 0.2 percent to 4,689.  Mining shares: A measure of primary metals traded in  London 
fell 0.4 percent.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, was little changed at A$41.65 in Sydney. Its American
depositary receipts fell 0.4 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-biggest miner,
rose 1.4 percent to A$83.20 in Sydney.  BHP may revive a takeover bid for Rio in 2013 should their
planned Australian iron-ore joint venture fail to get approval,
according to Sanford C. Bernstein Ltd.  Oil producers: Crude for November delivery fell 1.7 percent
to settle at $81.25 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, lost 0.1 percent to A$44.33.  Bank stocks: Australia’s largest lenders are revamping
funding strategies to focus on Asia as they seek to tap “vast”
capital pools in the region, the Australian Financial Review
reported, citing executives at the banks.  National Australia Bank Ltd.  (NAB AU), the nation’s biggest
business lender, dropped 0.7 percent to A$25.49.  AMP Ltd.  (AMP AU) and  Axa Asia Pacific Holdings Ltd.  (AXA
AU): Axa SA and AMP are making progress in continuing talks on
whether to make a bid for Axa Asia Pacific Holdings, the
Australian reported, without attribution. The two companies are
not poised to make a bid, the newspaper said. AMP shares gained
1.7 percent to A$5.36. AXA Asia Pacific was unchanged at A$5.16.  Centro Properties Group  (CNP AU): Centro is working on a
A$2 billion ($2 billion) sale of assets to allow its lenders to
recoup equity, the Sydney Morning Herald reported, citing
analysts and unidentified people familiar with the situation.
The stock was unchanged at 16 Australian cents.  Dexus Property Group  (DXS AU): Dexus Wholesale Property
Fund bought 13 Australian industrial properties with tenants
including Mercedes-Benz and Fairfax Media Ltd. for A$231 million
and signaled plans to sell as much as A$500 million in shares.  Dexus Wholesale is an unlisted trust managed by Dexus
Property Group, Australia’s largest owner and manager of office
properties, whose shares were unchanged at 83.5 Australian cents.  Coca-Cola Amatil Ltd.  (CCL AU) and  Foster’s Group Ltd.  (FMG
AU): Coca-Cola doesn’t see any value in a bid for Foster’s Group
Ltd. at current prices because it would make it difficult to
generate a return, the Australian newspaper reported, citing
Amatil Chief Executive Officer  Terry Davis .  Coca-Cola shares climbed 0.3 percent to A$12.24. Foster’s
sank 0.5 percent to A$6.04.  To contact the reporter for this story:
 Shani Raja  in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net ;  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 